review_blob: A bit of skunk in the aroma, but otherwise clean. Pleasantly hoppy without the bitterness, refreshing, and light. Some minerality and dryness in the finish.

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: Honey, apple, and toasted biscuit aromas. Aside from typical banana and clove flavors familiar to the style, this beer also has a noticeable floral characteristic with just a hint of bitterness. Chewy and thicker than most, and perhaps a bit darker than most, this is probably the best hefeweizen Ive had to date.

Aroma sweet, bready, like caramel and sugarcane. After an initial bite of carbonation, sweet malt flavors kick in with a pleasantly bitter mild hop finish. Relatively low alcohol content makes this a good post-dinner sessioner.
Hard toast malt aroma and flavor, mild hop flavor and bitterness. Rather on the dark side for an amber, this beer is both refreshing and filling, and great in cold or warm weather.
Deliciously tart, not too sweet, and subtly appley. A little bit of wood and smoke on the nose, not too strong, and a juxtaposition of creamy first taste and bright minerality in the finish.
beer_name: Angry Orchard Strawman Farmhouse Hard Cider

review_blob: Piney aroma with malt notes, a sweetish malt flavor with some fruit, and moderate-to-high bitterness. Drinks smooth after several IPAs, and I mean that as a complement.

beer_brewer_name: Portland Brewing Company (Pyramid - North American Breweries)
review_blob: Amber in color, with a hoppy, honeyed aroma, and biscuity, yet watery flavor.
Golden, dry, with lots of variations on hop flavor: citrus, grass, planty, and lemony. Kind of like a study in hops.

Interestingly enough for an IPA, it came unfiltered. Which was a little unfortunate, given its resultant appearance and yeasty aroma. However, I could appreciate its citrusy, tart flavor on a hot summer day.
Bready aroma, with the following flavors: coffee, chocolate, caramel, licorice. Tart, sweet and refreshing.
Big hop nose as expected. Hopping methods suggest and taste confirms high hop bitterness with only moderate real hop flavor. What else can I say? HOPS.
Strong coffee aroma and first taste, which develops into a distinct grainy bitterness and a chocolatey aftertaste. Interesting idea, but a little disjointed.
Citrusy hop aroma, a sweet piney hops flavor, and toasty malts. Well balanced and mighty tasty.
Delicious pilsner. Hardly any aroma of note, with mild floral hop flavors and a slightly earthy malt character.

High dose of hops, with a burnt bitter malt flavor. Bitterness was definitely malt-derived and a little overbearing. The hops and malt flavors seem to be in balance but arent coming together well for me.
Mild, floral hop aroma and taste with clean and refreshing maltiness. Thoroughly enjoyable.
Sweet, with biscuity malt flavors and minimal hop bitterness.

Hoppy aroma, grassy along with a hint of fresh-cut grass. The flavor is supremely hoppy, sweet and spicy. No overtly bitter aftertaste for an IPA, which is impressive. Maui definitely played this one right.
Blood orange in color. Flowery, honeyed aroma. Effervescent hoppy flavor with distinct sweet hibiscus and mild saffron aftertaste. Light and refreshing.
Starts off with a malty and sweet, almost rumcake-like aroma. Reddish brown. Strong, sweet and malty. Caramel and toast aftertaste, with some alcohol burn. Did I mention it was sweet and malty?
Nutty aroma, chocolate and almonds prominent. Sweet, malty, a roast nut taste, a little watery and light, but drinkable. Not a lot of complexity; one-dimensional.
Tamarind aroma, some caramelized sugar. Watery, earthy taste with mild bitterness. Unexpected rich, toasty aftertaste.

Powerful chipotle and smoke aroma, a bit deceptive for the degree of initial flavor imparted. Delivers a spicy kick in the back of the throat that lingers for much longer than it should. Thats really all there is to it. Its fairly heavy bodied for a blonde lager, and not carbonated enough.
Very interesting. Tawny brown. Cherry, dried rose and cumin aromas, with flavors of puckering citrus, tobacco, tamarind, and sour cherries. But somehow, it worked.
Light, refreshingly hoppy with chocolate flavors and smoke. Peppery and sweet. Coffee aroma.
beer_name: Bear Republic / Fat Heads / Stone TBA

review_blob: Some honey sweetness tempered by malty fullness and earth. Also some leathery notes and metallic mineral flavors, with a touch of spice. I didnt notice too much of an aroma beyond a hint of sweetness.
Aroma a combination of hoppy bitterness and fresh cut grass. Strong hop flavor, but with the honeyed richness of the toasted malt, and a restrained astringency.
beer_name: Stone / The Alchemist / Ninkasi More Brown than Black IPA

review_blob: Surprisingly complex. Perhaps the most complex beer Ive had. Almost everything on the label comes out and is presented well. Aroma starts with the grassy spiciness of the fenugreek before bringing forward sweeter birch and earthy, sweet yam. The flavor is initially sweet pumpkin, moving into a toasty spice mixed with an astringent citrusy aftertaste, likely from the verbena. The only downside is that the mouthfeel is a bit soapy and leaves an odd stale taste in the back of the throat. Perhaps after adding fenugreek and verbena Mitch could have cut the hops in half. But all in all, I would drink this again.
beer_name: Bruery / Elysian / Stone La Citrueille Cleste de Citracado

review_blob:
Rich aroma of melted dark chocolate and fresh oak. First flavors of raisins, followed by chocolate, honey, saffron, and finally fresh black coffee. Some bitterness lingers midpalate. This makes for a great dessert beer to be paired with cheesecake. I wish I had some right now.

If there is a negative here, its opaque. I would have liked to see a touch of color. Being an incarnation of Rasputin, however, I should expect this inky blackness.

Inky black with just a touch of head. Not much for aroma, but a great toasty flavor, with some bitterness contributed by the hops. Also, a touch of oak midpalate. Ever so slightly oily, otherwise smooth. Quite good.
Dark chocolate, raw leather, burnt toast aromas, with coffee and bitter roasted malts flavors, some hop character. A little flat.
beer_name: Six Rivers Paradise Moon Coffee Porter

review_blob: Bubblegum flavor, heavily cilantro, hint of clove aftertaste, with cola and slight florality. Yeasty and citrusy aroma.
Chocolate aroma. Shoeshine, cedar, strong bubblegum flavor, with a mild malty aftertaste.
Licorice and cola aroma, with hints of jgermeister, caramel, and tootsie roll. Prune, rye, tart cherry flavor, sour, with cumin notes. Puckering.
Faint bubblegum aroma, black peppery. Tart and sweet initially, intense honey and mead flavors midpalate, with a turnaround smoky malt aftertaste. Real smooth.
Sweet, but not excessively so. Marshmellowy. Some coriander and mild stale hop spice, but overall an odd balance of flavors.

Right off, powerful malty, biscuity aromas wafting up, along with honey. The flavor, likewise, was intensely sweet, richly toasty, honeyed, and contained hints of grape and saffron. Dry at the finish. Completely worth it, either at room temperature or gently chilled.

Awesome, epic hop and chocolate aroma (like hershey chocolate, not fancy chocolate), with some maple. Solid black, opaque, tan head. The first sip is intensely sweet without astringency, some smoke, some tobacco. There is also a biscuity aftertaste that reminds  That being said, this beer will put hair on your chest. The bitterness is not to be taken lightly and the hop flavor is prominent. Still, this beer is absolutely delicious and I look forward to seeing what they come up with next.
beer_name: Stone 15th Anniversary Escondidian Imperial Black IPA

review_blob: This is essentially a high-gravity porter. An aroma of dark chocolate turns into a flavor melding chocolate, coffee, and cola, along with just a touch of smoke. A mild, fresh hop flavor rounds out the taste profile. As the beer gets warmer the cola sweetness becomes more prominent. This is a beer whose flavors develop as it starts out ice cold and gets warmer, and gets tastier with time. Impressive.
beer_name: Sierra Nevada / Dogfish Head Life & Limb

review_blob: Although relatively light and uncomplex for any Belgian style, this dubbel is nonetheless pleasantly sweet with a good malt profile and a touch of hoppiness. Not very aromatic. A tad heavy in the palate for the flavor.

Pale gold in color. Aroma of rosewater and other floral scents. Bitter, but light, and very refreshing. Clearly the hops were the star here, but there was a clear hint of wheat somewhere in the background. Perfect level of smoothness while managing to stay light on the tongue.
Orange-gold. Honey and rose aroma. Somewhat booze forward, with strong caramel and banana flavors accompanied by grassy hop undertones. Need I say more?
Not bad for a conglomerate beer. Really, more malty than expected, with the typical improperly-stored-lager skunk, but not overly pronounced. A moderately bitter hop finish.

Tawny red in color, with an aroma of heather honey, bread, and hazelnuts. More honey in the swig, along with rosemary and rich malts without excessive heaviness. Moderate bitterness and grassy hops round out a flawless barleywine.

Sweet, malty, and rather nutty. Way different from the West Coast style pale ale that Im used to, this one is much more English-style in character and has a mild grassy hop flavor and a thinner mouth feel. Good enough for a beer or three in the balmy St. Louis summer.
Light and refreshing, with a lovely mild jasmine flavor and a bit of nuttiness. Minimal floral hops against a decent malt backdrop to support the sweet, flowery flavors.

Tasty, tasty, tasty start to Oakquinox this year. Opaque like motor oil with a honey-colored head. Strong malt and coffee aromas, with a touch of smoke. Not excessively sweet for its strength, lots of coffee and raw cacao flavors along with a steamroller of a mouthfeel. This beer literally coats your mouth. Peaty, smoky aftertaste following a surprising slick finish. Yum.

Meh. The apple flavor was just too overpowering for this to be good. Flavors were all over the place, hops were way overbalanced, body was thin and fragile and could not stand up to the top-heavy flavors at all. Brandy added some funkiness as well. Alcohol definitely present and contributed sickly-sweet off-flavors in the aftertaste. Props for originality, but the beer is not worth the effort.

My favorite brew at Oakquinox BY FAR. Sour but not puckering. Sweet but not cloying. Just enough use of hops to bring out the floral, rosy, honey flavors, and some very mild bitterness. Some fruit crosses the palate, likely from the Syrah, which probably contributes some color too. The Syrah also adds a touch of structure and earthiness to what otherwise might have been a thinner, "floaty" beer. Gimme more!

Intensely sweet, yet smooth and not sticky or burning like the Tokyo* (my point of comparison from last years Oakquinox). Dark chocolate predominates with some coffee and leather. This is probably one of my favorite RIS now.
